The USPSTF concludes that the evidence is insufficient to determine the balance of benefits and harms of screening mammography in women 75 years or older.</p><p><b>code</b>: <span title="Codes:{http://cancerscreeningcds.github.io/bcsm-cds/CodeSystem/plan-definition-action-code-system sdmcontinue}">Shared decision making to continue screening</span></p><h3>Documentations</h3><table class="grid"><tr><td style="display: none">-</td><td><b>Type</b></td><td><b>Label</b></td><td><b>Display</b></td><td><b>Citation</b></td><td><b>Url</b></td></tr><tr><td style="display: none">*</td><td>Citation</td><td>USPSTF</td><td>Screening for Breast Cancer: US Preventive Services Task Force Recommendation Statement</td><td><div><p>US Preventive Services Task Force. Screening for Breast Cancer: US Preventive Services Task Force Recommendation Statement. JAMA. Published online April 30, 2024.</p>
</div></td><td><a href="https://www.uspreventiveservicestaskforce.org/uspstf/recommendation/breast-cancer-screening">https://www.uspreventiveservicestaskforce.org/uspstf/recommendation/breast-cancer-screening</a></td></tr></table><p><b>resource</b>: <a href="Bundle-DecisionToScreen_act-sdmcontinueage_act-sdmcontinuelifexp_end-decisionhighrisk.html#CommunicationRequest_277">Bundle: type = collection</a></p></blockquote><blockquote><p><b>action</b></p><blockquote><p><b>id</b></p>SDMContinueScreeningLifeExp</blockquote><p><b>title</b>: Shared decision making to continue screening based on life expectancy</p><p><b>description</b>: Decision to continue screening mammography in cases of limited life expectancy should be based on shared decision-making.

ACS advises that women should continue screening mammography as long as their overall health is good and they have a life expectancy of 10 years or more.

Life expectancy is generally defined as having greater than a 50% probability of surviving 10 years. A validated tool such as www.eprognosis.com can help guide decision making.</p><p><b>code</b>: <span title="Codes:{http://cancerscreeningcds.github.io/bcsm-cds/CodeSystem/plan-definition-action-code-system sdmcontinue}">Shared decision making to continue screening</span></p><h3>Documentations</h3><table class="grid"><tr><td style="display: none">-</td><td><b>Type</b></td><td><b>Label</b></td><td><b>Display</b></td><td><b>Citation</b></td><td><b>Url</b></td></tr><tr><td style="display: none">*</td><td>Citation</td><td>ACS</td><td>Breast Cancer Screening for Women at Average Risk: 2015 Guideline Update From the American Cancer Society</td><td><div><p>Saslow D, Boetes C, Burke W, Harms S, Leach MO, Lehman CD, Morris E, Pisano E, Schnall M, Sener S, Smith RA, Warner E, Yaffe M, Andrews KS, Russell CA; American Cancer Society Breast Cancer Advisory Group. American Cancer Society guidelines for breast screening with MRI as an adjunct to mammography. CA Cancer J Clin. 2007 Mar-Apr;57(2):75-89.</p>
